**Agilent Technologies**
Growth Trends Healthy, But Gross and Operating Margins Both Disappoint

3Q was the definition of a mixed bag with core growth well above, while margins disappointed (tariffs, variable pay, investments) with a similar story on 2025 guidance (growth higher, but not flowing to EPS). Commentary was generally upbeat around FY26, including B2B>1, however, the margin recovery magnitude (relative to 100 bps plus) and pace (1H/2H) will be key. Comfort on margin recovery and hiring the new CFO will likely be needed for investors to step in.

**Revenues** **above,** **margins** **disappoint.** Revenues of $1.74B were +4% vs. consensus, with core growth (+6.1%) above guidance (+1.7-3.6%), which the company reiterated in mid-July. By segment:LDG grew +7% led by LC/LCMS and NASD (+high-20s), ACG +5% with +MSD consumables and services, while AMG grew +5% driven by GC/GCMS. Down the P&L, GM of 53.1% fell 290 bps y/y due to FX, tariffs and downtime at Biovectra, with OPM down -230 bps y/y to 25.1%. On the bottom line, $1.37 EPS was at top-end of guide but disappointed given the margin compression (and $0.01 benefit from interest income).

**2025 revenue and core growth better, but not flowing to EPS.** Agilent raised '25 revenue guidance by +$150M at the midpoint, which assumes +4.3-4.6% core growth (vs. +2.5-3.5% prior). EPS was narrowed to $5.56-5.59 with the midpoint ($5.58) unchanged vs. prior guidance despite the better top-line and benefit from interest income (+$0.04), partly due to a higher net tariff impact ($20M vs. minimal prior/-$0.07 headwind). Biovectra guidance also ticked down slightly (timing, growth still mid-teens). For 4Q, he company guided to revenues of $1.82-1.84B (+$60M vs. consensus), with core growth of +5.4% at the midpoint (+180 bps above expectations), while EPS captured the Street at the top-end of the range ($1.57-1.60). By end-market, guidance assumes pharma +M/HSD, CAM +HSD, dx/clinical +MSD, food +MSD, environmental and forensics +LSD, A&G -MSD. Adj. OPM are expected to be +200 bps q/q to ~27%.

**Biopharma** **color.** Biopharma grew +9% (closer to flat ex. NASD), accelerating on the 2-yr stack vs. 1H25 trends (+LSD vs. -HSD). LCMS grew +LDD, with Infinity 3 up mid-teens. NASD grew high-20% due to both clinical and commercial with increased confidence around the ability to grow +OD in '25 and carry momentum into '26 partly due to recent approvals (e.g. ALNY's Amvuttra). Biovectra was in-line with expectations and down q/q. Importantly, Agilent noted a reduced dependency on executive approvals that has been stalling purchases, with improved velocity of budgets/quotes and an uptick in replacement cycle activity in July/August.

**Other...1) PFASs** +LDD with strength ex. U.S. (+>30%) offset by U.S. weakness (-20%) due to EPA dynamics with a "little bit" of impact expected in 4Q/1Q26; **2)** China: stable (+4% in 3Q), with biopharma +MSD (small molecule +6%), while CAM was up low-teens (petro chem, semis) with a new government innovation program set to benefit the company (already seeing quotes); 3) Pricing: +100bps y/y (instruments better in 3Q).

**Priya Patel*|Equity Associate**
**Lauren Timmins, Ph.D.*|Equity Associate**

The near- term demand backdrop for Agilent is improving, with growth engine starting to pick up again. That said, the choppiness on margins (3Q25 clear example) leaves some pause with some clarity around the ability to grow adj. OPM in 2026 (and the magnitude / cadence) likely needed before investors step in. We think combination of growth re- rating and margin improvement needed to drive multiple to re- rate higher.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

FY25 revs: \(+4.5\%\) organic growth FY26 revs: \(\sim +5.5\%\) organic growth \(\sim 27\%\) OPM in FY26 / \(\sim 35\%\) incremental going forward FY25E EPS: \(\) 5.57\(FY26E EPS:\) \ \(5.95\) Price Target: \(\) 120\(implies\) \sim 15x \(FY26E EBITDA

FY25 revs: \(+6\%\) organic growth FY26 revs: \(+6.7\%\) organic \(\sim 500\) bps OPM expansion through 2034 More China stimulus in \(25 / 26\) Instrument rebound picked up 2H25 and 2026 NASD growth accelerates toward \(\sim +20\%\) Price Target: \(\) 145=\sim 18x\(FY26E EBITDA

FY25 revs: \(+2.3\%\) organic growth FY26 revs: \(+3.4\%\) organic Inability to drive adj. OPM expansion in meaningful way No follow- on rounds of China stimulus NASD growth algo challenged (lower \(\) 1B\(by CDMO target) Price Target:\) \ \(95 = \sim 12x\) FY26E EBITDA

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Supply chain management. Agilent has invested in expanded NASD capacity and committed to automation and engineering enhancements, which include water reclamation, solar energy, and solvent waste capturing and recycling to promote a more sustainable supply chain. 2) Product quality & safety are particularly important when moving from more air to sea shipping. Agilent has invested in vacuum seal and moisture barrier bags to maintain product quality in transit.

Company Target(s): 1) Net- zero greenhouse gas emissions by 2050. By 2030, reduce Scope 1 and 2 emissions by \(50\%\) (vs. 2019 levels). 2) Strategically invest in renewable energy - purchased goods and services, transportation.

Questions to Management: 1) What investments are you making to achieve net- zero GHG emissions, and how is your spend in this area going to trend in the next 5 years? 2) Have longer shipping lead times for products transported by sea led to any supply chain issues, or is it mostly mitigated through buffer stock?
New NASD capacity expansion coming online, ramp of commercial programs, and success of later stage Phase 3s
Durable growth inflection in instruments/LSAG as replacement cycle kicks in
China stimulus (second wave, likely to hit in 2H25). M&A activity
Source: Agilent and Jefferies LLC estimates.
Agilent TechnologiesAgilent is a leading manufacturer of instruments, software, and consumables serving the life sciences, diagnostics, and applied chemical markets.

Our \(\) 120\(PT represents a 10 - year horizon in our DCF model and implies 20x FY26E EPS and EV of \~15x EBITDA. Downside Risks: longer instrument cycle, missed M&A opportunities, prolonged China recovery. Upside Risks: margins surprised to upside on cost - outs, larger buyback, NASD demand on commercial side snaps back.
Our PT blends DCF and probability- adjusted EPS analyses. Risks include efficacy, commercial, and competition.
